    {
      "type": "header",
      "level": 1,
      "text": "Louse-borne (Epidemic) Typhus"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "text": "Louse-borne typhus is a severe disease caused by Rickettsia prowazekii and transmitted by the human body louse. It has historically occurred in epidemics during times of war and famine."
    },
    {
      "type": "header",
      "level": 2,
      "text": "Clinical Manifestations"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "text": "Symptoms include abrupt onset of high fever, headache, and a maculopapular rash that begins on the trunk and spreads to the extremities, sparing the face, palms, and soles. Brill-Zinsser disease is a relapsing form of epidemic typhus that can occur years after the primary infection."
    },
    {
      "type": "header",
      "level": 2,
      "text": "Diagnosis"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "text": "Diagnosis is based on clinical findings and serological tests (IFA)."
    },
    {
      "type": "header",
      "level": 2,
      "text": "Treatment"
    },
    {
      "type": "drugRegimen",
      "regimenData": {
        "intent": "treatment",
        "strengthOfRecommendation": "Recommended",
        "appliesTo": {
          "description": "Adults and children with louse-borne typhus"
        },
